  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. Key requirements typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Implementing screening processes\n- Training staff on detection and prevention\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting customer information\n- Assessing risk levels\n- Ongoing customer monitoring\n\n5. Legal Penalties\n- Potential significant financial fines\n- Possible criminal prosecution\n- Risk of losing banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced by regulatory agencies like FinCEN in the United States and similar organizations internationally.\n\nSpecific requirements can vary by jurisdiction, but most developed financial systems have robust anti-money laundering frameworks designed to prevent financial crimes.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects of money laundering prevention?",
